    {
      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im working on a model and noticed my features have totally different scales. like one is 0-1 and another is 1000-5000. why do i actually need to normalize them before training? does it really matter that much?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, it matters a lot because neural networks are essentially gradient-based optimizers that can get confused if the scales of different features are vastly different. When one feature has a range of 0–1 and another has 1000–5000, the gradients for the larger-scale features will dominate the updates, causing the model to update weights for the small-scale features very slowly or not at all. This imbalance can lead to a very inefficient training process where the optimizer takes a long time to converge or gets stuck in a poor local minimum.\n\nIn short, normalizing features ensures that the distance between data points in the feature space is meaningful regardless of the original units, which helps the model learn much faster and more accurately. Without normalization, the model might end up ignoring important signals from the smaller-scale features entirely. While some modern optimizers are somewhat robust to this issue, it is still best practice to normalize your data to ensure stable and efficient training.",
